SUMMARY:Talking Conservation: Janet McCabe
DESCRIPTION:Janet McCabe\, former Deputy Administrator of the U.S. Enviro
 nmental Protection Agency and current Professor of Practice at Indiana Un
 iversity\, will deliver a lecture titled "Connections and Consequences: F
 ederal Environmental Policy and State-Level Impacts." She will discuss ho
 w federal environmental policy is interpreted\, implemented\, and enforce
 d at the state level. Drawing on her experience in both federal and state
  government\, she will explore the opportunities and challenges of transl
 ating national environmental laws into meaningful protections on the grou
 nd\, with particular attention to Indiana and the Midwest.About "Talking 
 Conservation"  Talking Conservation is a public education series from Con
 servation Law Center that explores pressing issues in environmental and c
 onservation law\, with an emphasis on Indiana and the Midwest. Hosted in 
 Bloomington and recorded for online viewing\, each event features expert 
 voices from across the conservation landscapeâ€”legal advocates\, scienti
 sts\, policymakers\, and community leadersâ€”sharing insights on topics r
 anging from clean water and habitat protection to land conservation and p
 ublic interest lawyering for the environment.  Through these engaging\, a
 ccessible lectures\, Conservation Law Center aims to inform\, inspire\, a
 nd empower the public to better understand and influence the legal and po
 licy frameworks that shape the natural world we share.&#160\;About the sp
 eaker:Janet McCabe is an environmental policy expert with a distinguished
  career in public service\, law\, and academia. From April 2021 to Octobe
 r 2024\, she served as the deputy administrator of the United States Envi
 ronmental Protection Agency (EPA)\, where she played a key role in shapin
 g the nation's environmental policies and oversaw all aspects of manageme
 nt of the agency and its workforce.From 2017 to 2021\, McCabe was a profe
 ssor of practice at the Indiana University McKinney School of Law and dir
 ected the IU Environmental Resilience Institute (ERI)\, where she began a
 s assistant director for policy and implementation in 2017. She rejoined 
 the Indiana University faculty in summer 2025 with a joint appointment at
  McKinney Law\, O'Neill School of Public and Environmental Affairs\, and 
 the ERI.McCabe also served at the EPA starting in 2009\, as principal dep
 uty to the assistant administrator of the Office of Air and Radiation (OA
 R). She served as acting assistant administrator for OAR from 2013 throug
 h 2016. Her leadership at the EPA was instrumental in advancing critical 
 air quality and climate change initiatives during President Obama's two t
 erms.Before her work at the EPA\, McCabe was executive director of Improv
 ing Kids' Environment\, Inc.\, an environmental health advocacy organizat
 ion focused on children's health. From 1993 to 2005\, McCabe held various
  leadership roles in the Indiana Department of Environmental Management's
  Office of Air Quality\, including assistant commissioner for that office
 .Before to moving to Indianapolis in 1993\, McCabe was assistant attorney
  general for environmental protection in Massachusetts and the assistant 
 secretary for environmental impact review\, managing Massachusetts' envir
 onmental review statute. She began her legal career clerking for Justice 
 Neil L. Lynch of the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court.She was raised 
 in Washington\, D.C.\, and attended Harvard College and Harvard Law Schoo
 l.RSVP below to attend.&#160\;
