SUMMARY:What Really was the Original Understanding of Freedom of the Pres
 s and Speech?
DESCRIPTION:Professor David Forte of Cleveland State University College o
 f Law\, joined by Professor Joseph Tomain\, will discuss the origins of t
 he protections the First Amendment affords the freedom of the press and s
 peech. For generations\, scholars have been exercised over whether the Fi
 rst Amendment forbids laws criminalizing seditious libelâ€“that is\, laws
  that punish criticism of the government. But the First Amendment meant m
 uch more than that issue to the Framers. When we go back to the first pri
 nciples underlying freedom of speech\, we can at last determine what the 
 Framers meant to protect and what they would have allowed the government 
 to regulate. Join us for a conversation on the first principles of the fr
 eedom of speech and press\, and the future of the First Amendment.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><span style="font-family: 'Arial'\,sans-s
 erif\; color: black\;">Professor David Forte of Cleveland State Universit
 y College of Law\, joined by Professor Joseph Tomain\, will discuss the o
 rigins of the protections the First Amendment affords the freedom of the 
 press and speech. For generations\, scholars have been exercised over whe
 ther the First Amendment forbids laws criminalizing seditious libelâ€“tha
 t is\, laws that punish criticism of the government. But the First Amendm
 ent meant much more than that issue to the Framers. When we go back to th
 e first principles underlying freedom of speech\, we can at last determin
 e what the Framers meant to protect and what they would have allowed the 
 government to regulate. Join us for a conversation on the first principle
 s of the freedom of speech and press\, and the future of the First Amendm
 ent.</span></p>
